Certainly! Here's an example of how you can create a configurable card template using a custom Lovelace card written in JavaScript in Home Assistant:

1. Create a new JavaScript file for your custom Lovelace card. For example, `configurable-card.js`.

2. In the JavaScript file, define the card structure and functionality using the Lovelace custom card API. Here's a basic example:

```javascript
class ConfigurableCard extends HTMLElement {
  setConfig(config) {
    if (!config || !config.entities) {
      throw new Error('Invalid configuration');
    }

    const root = this.attachShadow({ mode: 'open' });

    // Create card elements
    const card = document.createElement('ha-card');
    const content = document.createElement('div');
    const title = document.createElement('h1');
    title.textContent = config.title || 'Configurable Card';

    // Populate card with entities
    config.entities.forEach(entityId => {
      const entityWrapper = document.createElement('div');
      const entityState = document.createElement('span');
      entityState.textContent = entityId;
      entityWrapper.appendChild(entityState);
      content.appendChild(entityWrapper);
    });

    // Append elements to shadow DOM
    root.appendChild(card);
    card.appendChild(content);
    card.appendChild(title);
  }
}

customElements.define('configurable-card', ConfigurableCard);
```

3. Save the `configurable-card.js` file.

4. In your Home Assistant configuration, add the following to reference your custom card:

```yaml
resources:
  - url: /local/configurable-card.js
    type: module
```

5. Restart Home Assistant to load the custom card.

6. Configure the card in your Lovelace configuration by creating a new card with the following options:

```yaml
type: 'custom:configurable-card'
entities:
  - light.bedroom
  - light.living_room
title: Example Configurable Card
```

7. Save the Lovelace configuration.

Now, you have a configurable card template that displays the entities specified in the Lovelace config. You can modify the list of entities and title in the Lovelace config, and the card will update accordingly. You can also further customize the `setConfig` method in the JavaScript file to support additional config options or interact with Home Assistant entities in a more sophisticated way.
